	\includegraphics[scale=.9]{trisymknotandlink2}
	\caption{Tri-symmetric projections of a $2$-bridge link with two components (left) and a $2$-bridge knot (right). The axes of symmetry for $\sigma_{1}$ and $\sigma_{2}$ are given in both projections. Maxima are labeled M and minima are labeled m.}
	\label{fig:trysim}
\end{figure}

 If $\Omega$ is palindromic, then there are additional elements in $Sym(M)$, as noted in Theorem \ref{thm:Symclass}. In these cases, $Sym(M)$ is isomorphic to either $D_{4}$ or $Z_{2} \oplus Z_{2} \oplus Z_{2}$. Either way, $Sym(M)$ is a group of order eight. Since $Sym(M) \supseteq Sym(\mathbb{S}^{3}, K)$, we only need to show that $Sym(\mathbb{S}^{3}, K(\Omega))$ is also a group of order eight.

If $\Omega$ is palindromic, then we can isotope $K(\Omega)$ so that it exhibits a symmetry $\sigma_{3}$, as depicted in Figure \ref{palindromicsym}. We claim that $\sigma_{1}$, $\sigma_{2}$, and $\sigma_{3}$ generate a group of order eight. Since we already know that $\sigma_{1}$ and $\sigma_{2}$ generate a subgroup $H \subset Sym( \mathbb{S}^{3} \setminus K(\Omega))$ of order four, we just need to show that $\sigma_{3}$ is not an element of $H$. If this holds, then $\sigma_{3}$, $\sigma_{3} \circ \sigma_{1}$, $\sigma_{3} \circ \sigma_{2}$, and $\sigma_{3} \circ (\sigma_{1} \circ \sigma_{2})$ will give four more distinct elements of $Sym( \mathbb{S}^{3} \setminus K(\Omega))$, implying that this group has order eight. We will prove this by considering how these symmetries act on the maxima and minima of $K(\Omega)$. Note that, $\sigma_{1}$, $\sigma_{2}$ and $\sigma_{1} \circ \sigma_{2}$ only map maxima to maxima and minima to minima. This is true both when $K(\Omega)$ is a knot and when $K(\Omega)$ is a link with 2-components; see Figure \ref{fig:trysim}. However, in all three possible cases ($n$ is even, $n$ is odd with $\alpha_{\frac{n+1}{2}}$ even, or $n$ is odd with $\alpha_{\frac{n+1}{2}}$ odd), $\sigma_{3}$ exchanges each maxima with a minima; see Figure \ref{palindromicsym}. Thus, $\sigma_{3}$ is not an element of $H$, and we can conclude that $Sym(M) = Sym(\mathbb{S}^{3}, K(\Omega))$, when $\Omega$ is palindromic. 



